Fault Identification in Simulink

This example demonstrates how to estimate unknown inputs and states of a discrete-time, linear time-invariant (LTI) plant using the ULISE algorithm [1] in SimulinkÂ®. You will use the ULISE Filter and LTI Plant blocks to estimate the faults (unknown inputs or disturbances) and states [2].

Introduction:

In this example, we estimate the 3 faults and 5 internal states of a discrete-time LTI system.
The estimator handles both observable and unobservable fault components, estimating the unknown input with a one-step delay , while the state vector is estimated with zero-step delay [1] (or See ULISE Filter for more information).
The Simulink model shown below implements this workflow.
Figure 1: Simulink model of a discrete-time LTI plant using the ULISE Filter to estimate current states and one-step delay unknown inputs.
In general, the Simulink workflow will consists of two main components:
  1. Defining system and simulation parameters inside the initialization callback script.
  2. Using the LTI Plant and ULISE Filter blocks to set up and simulate the model workspace.

Initialization Callback Script:

To run this example, all system parameters and simulation settings are defined in the initialization script InitFcn_ULISE.m.
This script is automatically executed when the example model is run, ensuring consistent/updated parameterization.
For a general LTI system with n states , m known inputs , p unknown inputs , and l measured outputs , the file must define the following structures and fields:
Simulation Setup struct (SimSetup):
  • Simulation sample time Ts (default 1 second for discrete-time systems)
  • Total time steps K
  • Total simulation time T
  • Time vector t for generating timeseries objects
System struct (System):
  • State transition matrixA(n-by-n)
  • Control input matrix B (n-by-m)
  • Measurement matrix C(l-by-n)
  • Direct feedthrough from matrix D (l-by-m)
  • Disturbance input matrix G (n-by-p)
  • Disturbance feedthrough to output matrix H (n-by-p)
  • Process noise covariance Q (n-by-n)
  • Cholesky decomposition of Q, denoted cholQ
  • Measurement noise covariance R (l-by-l)
  • Cholesky decomposition of R, denoted cholR
  • Initial condition of the state , denoted x0
  • Initial states estimate, , denoted xhat0
  • Initial state error covariance, (n-by-n), denoted P_x0
Learn more ahout MATLAB's Cholesky decomposition function, chol.
Input Data Struct (InputData):
  • Timeseries object of the known input u matrix (m-by-K) where each column is at time step k
  • Timseries object of the unknown input d matrix (p-by-K) where each column is at time step k
Learn more about MATLAB's timeseries function.
Example excerpt (defining the unknown input d):
The following excerpt of code from InitFcn_ULISE.m illustrates how to do this for the unknown input d ().
% Initialize the input data struct
InputData = struct();
 
%% Simulate 'true' unknown input, d
d = zeros(p,SimSetup.K);
d(1,500:700) = 1*ones(size(d(1,500:700)));
 
for j = 100:800
d(2,j) = 1/700*(j-100);
end
 
% Modify the third disturbance component
d(3,[500:549 600:649 700:749]) = 3*ones(size(d(3,[500:549 600:649 700:749])));
d(3,[550:599 650:699 750:799]) = -3*ones(size(d(3,[550:599 650:699 750:799])));
 
% Add unknown input timeseries to struct
InputData.d = setinterpmethod(timeseries(d, SimSetup.t),'zoh');
InputData.d.Name = "timeseries unknown input";

The A matrix describes the system dynamics between consecutive time steps, while the C (a 5-by-5 identity matrix) indicates that all states are observable.
For modeling purposes, we assume that we don't have known input being added to our system i.e., , and so the B and D matrices are both (5-by-1) zero vectors.
Lastly, Q must be positive semi-definite and R must be a postive definite matrix to ensure valid (stochastic) modeling. The Cholesky decomposed Q and R are used to generate and , respectively.

ULISE Filter Design

The ULISE Filter estimates both the system states and the the unkown inputs of the LTI plant described above.
The estimator assumes the same discrete-time model structure:
,
.
The filter computes the following estimates:
  • : zero-step delay estimate of the state vector
  • : one-step delay estimate of the unknown input vector
The ULISE algorithm ensures unbiased state estimation if the three Assumptions are satisfied described in the ULISE Filter block documentation.
The filter is implemented in the ULISE Filter Simulink block. DDuring initialization, the block checks Assumptions (i), if the Control System Toolbox is installed, and it always checks assumption (ii).

Estimation Objective

The ULISE Filter computes the following estimates given the available measurements and known inputs :
  • : zero-step delay estimate of the state vector
  • : one-step delay estimate of the unknown input vector
This formulation allows accurate state and fault identification for systems subject to observable and unovervable faults.
This filter assumes the system satisfies the three Assumptions that produce unbiased and stable estimates of and , described in ULISE Filter block documentation. During initialization, the block checks Assumptions (i), if the Control System Toolbox is installed, and it always checks assumption (ii).
